data.content:
These are two distinct C# 15 breaking changes:

## Error 1: `&&` with `dynamic` and interface operators

The `&&` operator is synthesized from `operator true`/`operator false` + `operator &`. When `right` is `dynamic`, the compiler must defer operator resolution to the **DLR** (Dynamic Language Runtime) at runtime. However, the DLR predates static interface methods and **cannot dispatch `operator true`/`operator false` defined on an interface type** like `IFilter`.

C# 15 now reports this at compile time instead of generating code that would fail at runtime.

**Fix** — avoid mixing interface-defined truth operators with `dynamic`:
```csharp
// Option A: use explicit logic instead of &&
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    dynamic combined = IFilter.op_False(left) ? left : (dynamic)left & right;
}

// Option B: work with concrete types
void Apply(CompositeFilter left, CompositeFilter right) { var c = left && right; }
```

## Error 2: `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518

`CS0518` means a **predefined/well-known BCL type is missing**. C# 15 changed how `ref readonly` returns are encoded in synthesized delegate types for lambdas, now requiring a new compiler-services attribute type (for metadata representation of the ref-readonly return).

This is typically an **SDK ↔ runtime version mismatch** — your compiler targets a well-known type that isn't in your runtime libraries yet (common in preview builds).

**Fix**:
```csharp
// Workaround: use a named method + explicit delegate type
delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();

private static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;

public static void M()
{
    RefReadOnlyFunc fn = GetValue;  // works — no synthesized delegate needed
}
```

Or ensure your SDK and runtime preview versions are aligned (`dotnet --info` to verify).
